1
00:00:45,200 --> 00:00:47,300
If you add too much water,

2
00:00:47,727 --> 00:00:49,140
the dough loses its elasticity.

3
00:00:50,300 --> 00:00:50,840
Ugh.

4
00:00:51,106 --> 00:00:53,799
How am I supposed to know when it’s just right?

5
00:00:55,263 --> 00:00:57,760
Why isn’t there a formula for this like in math?

6
00:00:58,443 --> 00:00:59,000
Ugh.

7
00:01:30,001 --> 00:01:30,540
Nice.

8
00:01:31,667 --> 00:01:34,604
Another failed method.

9
00:01:48,679 --> 00:01:51,779
You always manage to surprise me.

10
00:01:53,433 --> 00:01:54,060
What?

11
00:01:54,558 --> 00:01:55,466
What did I do this time?

12
00:01:56,537 --> 00:01:58,420
The fact that you’re sitting here.

13
00:01:58,622 --> 00:02:00,340
Yesterday, you said

14
00:02:00,790 --> 00:02:02,790
you didn’t like doing anything emotional.

15
00:02:04,115 --> 00:02:08,760
I’m just joining one of the resort activities included in the package.

16
00:02:08,894 --> 00:02:09,960
That’s all.

17
00:02:10,162 --> 00:02:10,662
Wow.

18
00:02:10,662 --> 00:02:13,900
But with that expression, it looks like someone forced you to come.

19
00:02:14,581 --> 00:02:16,340
If anyone walks by,

20
00:02:16,625 --> 00:02:17,920
they’ll misunderstand

21
00:02:18,071 --> 00:02:21,280
and think I forced guests to make Bualoy.

22
00:02:22,015 --> 00:02:22,515
Hey.

23
00:02:22,874 --> 00:02:24,540
Haven’t you heard?

24
00:02:24,758 --> 00:02:27,740
Writers need to keep learning new things all the time.

25
00:02:28,266 --> 00:02:32,340
Everything can become useful for writing.

26
00:02:32,856 --> 00:02:33,380
Wow.

27
00:02:34,237 --> 00:02:34,737
Hey.

28
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:37,780
So your next book will be called

29
00:02:37,864 --> 00:02:42,013
“Ten Theories on How to Shape Dough Without It Sticking to Your Hands”?

30
00:02:47,600 --> 00:02:50,280
You’ve probably seen people make this a lot, right?

31
00:02:50,984 --> 00:02:51,374
Yeah.

32
00:02:51,374 --> 00:02:53,960
Hundreds, maybe thousands of times.

33
00:02:54,597 --> 00:02:55,280
Good then.

34
00:02:55,680 --> 00:02:57,027
Come help me.

35
00:02:57,112 --> 00:02:59,330
Then we can find out

36
00:02:59,614 --> 00:03:00,580
where this theory went wrong.

37
00:03:00,806 --> 00:03:01,963
Why should I help?

38
00:03:02,171 --> 00:03:02,671
Well,

39
00:03:02,783 --> 00:03:04,340
if you don’t help me,

40
00:03:04,449 --> 00:03:05,940
I’ll sit here complaining

41
00:03:06,003 --> 00:03:07,100
until other guests misunderstand

42
00:03:07,100 --> 00:03:09,460
and think you forced me to do this.

43
00:03:19,377 --> 00:03:20,360
So, what do I do?

44
00:03:28,385 --> 00:03:30,020
Do you actually know how to do this?

45
00:03:30,404 --> 00:03:31,100
I do.

46
00:03:35,033 --> 00:03:36,566
And then?

47
00:03:38,977 --> 00:03:41,529
Check if the texture feels right.

48
00:03:41,529 --> 00:03:44,895
If it does, stop. If not, add more.

49
00:03:46,551 --> 00:03:47,814
Is this enough?

50
00:03:50,141 --> 00:03:50,802
Not yet.

51
00:03:52,130 --> 00:03:54,130
Then add more flour.

52
00:03:59,031 --> 00:04:02,994
Hey, are you messing with me?

53
00:04:02,994 --> 00:04:04,546
No.

54
00:04:07,412 --> 00:04:10,701
Your hands just need more flour on them.

55
00:04:39,209 --> 00:04:40,196
See?

56
00:04:40,648 --> 00:04:43,000
You said you’d seen this hundreds of times.

57
00:04:43,001 --> 00:04:47,010
Then why do you look so pitiful doing it?

58
00:04:47,846 --> 00:04:49,759
When did I ever say I was good at it?

59
00:04:49,760 --> 00:04:50,362
Huh?

60
00:04:50,647 --> 00:04:53,891
You said you’d seen it hundreds of times.

61
00:04:54,627 --> 00:04:57,709
I said I’d seen it hundreds of times.

62
00:04:57,709 --> 00:04:59,737
That doesn’t mean I can do it.

63
00:05:01,026 --> 00:05:03,759
Then let me ask scientifically.

64
00:05:04,111 --> 00:05:06,045
What’s wrong with this equation?

65
00:05:06,782 --> 00:05:10,580
The problem is that it’s not an equation. It’s art.

66
00:05:11,189 --> 00:05:14,846
And it seems like you’re not very good at this kind of thing.

67
00:05:15,316 --> 00:05:18,705
Some things require feelings, not just logic.

68
00:05:37,980 --> 00:05:42,617
Why is it that every time I’m close to you,

69
00:05:43,290 --> 00:05:45,290
my brain isn't braining?

70
00:05:51,262 --> 00:05:54,580
Then stop using your brain.

71
00:05:55,601 --> 00:05:57,976
Try using your heart instead.

72
00:07:32,419 --> 00:07:34,498
Please, go ahead.

73
00:07:35,751 --> 00:07:38,253
Wait... what is all this?

74
00:07:38,566 --> 00:07:41,564
Seriously, why does everything seem so formal today?

75
00:07:41,748 --> 00:07:43,972
The chef wanted to thank both of you

76
00:07:43,973 --> 00:07:46,843
for helping cook the other day.

77
00:07:47,332 --> 00:07:49,780
Please, have a seat first.

78
00:07:56,438 --> 00:08:01,701
Today’s special menu is called
“Omakase: Ten Flavors of Emotions.”

79
00:08:02,722 --> 00:08:07,430
Honestly, it sounds more elegant than my book's title.

80
00:08:08,933 --> 00:08:11,352
The chef wanted to create a new menu

81
00:08:11,353 --> 00:08:14,491
especially for first-time guests staying here.

82
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:18,500
Don’t tell me this is the chef’s first experiment.

83
00:08:18,500 --> 00:08:21,610
Or are we secretly being used as test subjects?

84
00:08:23,066 --> 00:08:26,429
Why are you two getting along so well today?

85
00:08:27,115 --> 00:08:28,846
Chef, please serve the dishes.

86
00:08:44,635 --> 00:08:47,469
Please enjoy your meal. Excuse me for now.

87
00:10:23,267 --> 00:10:27,689
I keep trying to understand this feeling, but every time our eyes meet,

88
00:10:27,833 --> 00:10:31,206
she becomes the exception to every theory I’ve ever known.

89
00:10:31,767 --> 00:10:35,000
Because some feelings aren’t from reasons.

90
00:10:35,200 --> 00:10:39,075
They come from someone you never expected to feel this way about.

91
00:10:41,019 --> 00:10:43,347
So, how was the meal?

92
00:10:43,347 --> 00:10:47,178
It was delicious. Some things may seem bland on the outside,

93
00:10:47,179 --> 00:10:50,224
but once you taste them, there’s a hidden sweetness inside.

94
00:10:51,312 --> 00:10:53,579
Yes, it was amazing.

95
00:10:53,580 --> 00:10:57,723
Eating it feels like something that appears clear on the outside,

96
00:10:57,871 --> 00:11:01,461
but inside is so confusing that no equation could ever explain it.

97
00:11:01,615 --> 00:11:04,653
And they say Shakespeare is dead.

98
00:11:04,654 --> 00:11:06,654
You even compare food to emotions.

99
00:11:07,045 --> 00:11:09,118
Well, that’s because everything

100
00:11:09,119 --> 00:11:11,119
is finally starting to have flavor.

101
00:11:13,655 --> 00:11:17,905
If the two of us had a flavor,

102
00:11:18,384 --> 00:11:20,384
what flavor do you think we’d be?

103
00:11:23,066 --> 00:11:23,866
Hmm...

104
00:11:24,879 --> 00:11:26,688
A little bitter.

105
00:11:27,884 --> 00:11:29,884
But after swallowing it,

106
00:11:29,885 --> 00:11:31,885
a sweetness lingers inside.

107
00:12:04,871 --> 00:12:05,371
Hey...

108
00:12:06,081 --> 00:12:08,081
How did you get in here?

109
00:12:08,533 --> 00:12:10,598
Your door wasn’t locked.

110
00:12:11,033 --> 00:12:13,019
And it seemed like the owner of this room

111
00:12:13,087 --> 00:12:15,087
wanted someone to come in.

112
00:12:17,433 --> 00:12:20,296
I’m writing a book.

113
00:12:20,745 --> 00:12:24,101
Or maybe just trying to write one.

114
00:12:27,700 --> 00:12:29,044
Trying to write...

115
00:12:29,785 --> 00:12:32,823
or trying to run away from your feelings?

116
00:12:42,146 --> 00:12:43,927
I want to prove something.

117
00:12:46,763 --> 00:12:48,110
Prove what?

118
00:12:49,763 --> 00:12:51,467
That feelings

119
00:12:51,781 --> 00:12:54,534
don’t need a reason to exist.

120
00:12:57,410 --> 00:13:00,277
And... what if it’s wrong?

121
00:13:03,062 --> 00:13:05,662
Then we’ll be wrong together.

122
00:13:09,700 --> 00:13:10,360
Hey...

123
00:13:11,070 --> 00:13:14,426
Are you sure this feeling is real?

124
00:13:16,884 --> 00:13:18,418
If it needs logic,

125
00:13:19,463 --> 00:13:21,980
then it’s not really a feeling anymore.

126
00:13:25,251 --> 00:13:26,331
Then...

127
00:13:27,093 --> 00:13:28,700
there’s nothing left to prove.

128
00:13:29,778 --> 00:13:32,040
We just need to feel it.

129
00:15:33,963 --> 00:15:34,463
Am I...

130
00:15:34,859 --> 00:15:35,980
dreaming?

131
00:15:56,096 --> 00:15:57,163
So it was a dream...

132
00:16:25,385 --> 00:16:26,700
Did you sleep well?

133
00:16:28,311 --> 00:16:29,206
I did.

134
00:16:30,258 --> 00:16:31,460
It felt strange too.

135
00:16:32,259 --> 00:16:33,160
Strange how?

136
00:16:35,295 --> 00:16:38,820
Like dreaming about something I shouldn’t remember...

137
00:16:39,320 --> 00:16:41,009
but still can’t forget.

138
00:16:44,140 --> 00:16:45,500
I feel the same way.

139
00:17:22,467 --> 00:17:24,560
I thought she lived inside my head,

140
00:17:25,082 --> 00:17:27,900
but actually, she lives in my heart.

141
00:17:28,765 --> 00:17:32,140
Maybe dreams aren’t just things we think about while asleep.

142
00:17:32,682 --> 00:17:35,420
Maybe they’re what our hearts wish could become real,

143
00:17:35,564 --> 00:17:37,380
but we’re still too afraid to say out loud.

